JAPANESE ENCEPHALITIS AND OTHER - INDIA (17): (BIHAR)
*****************************************************

A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

In this update:
[1] Bihar
[2] NVBDC statistics as of 13 Sep 2011

******
[1]Bihar
Date: Wed 14 Sep 2011
Source: Yahoo News, Indo Asian News Service (IANS) report [edited]
http://in.news.yahoo.com/bihar-suspected-encephalitis-kills-six-more-080138810.html


With 6 more children dying, encephalitis is now suspected to have
claimed 25 young lives in Bihar, an official said Wednesday [14 Sep
2011]. The 6 children died in the last 2 days at Anugrah Narain
Medical College and Hospital (ANMCH) in Gaya, about 100 km [62 mi]
from [Patna], said the district health official. 19 children had died
earlier. The children reported high fever, followed by bouts of
unconsciousness and convulsions.

To date, more than 75 children with suspected encephalitis admitted,
to the hospital, said its superintendent, Sitaram Prasad. "Most of the
children were from rural areas of Gaya and neighbouring districts.
More than 2 dozen children are still battling for life," he said.

Measures were being taken to check the spread of the disease, said
Health Minister Ashwini Kumar Choubey.

Suspected encephalitis hit Gaya in 2009, 2007, and 2005 and killed
dozens of children, said a district administration official.

Fear of suspected encephalitis is haunting the Patna Medical College
and Hospital (PMCH) with 45 samples of brain fever cases having tested
positive in the last 1.5 months. 3 people reportedly died due to the
disease.

The state health department is running short of Japanese encephalitis
[JE] kits to test [for] the infection. "In view of seriousness of the
issue, ANMCH and PMCH have sent an SOS to the National Institute of
Virology, Pune, to send the kits soon," an official of the health
department told IANS.

2 months ago, 51 children died in Muzaffarpur district but the state
government is yet to confirm these as encephalitis deaths. Last month
[August 2011], union Health and Family Welfare Minister Ghulam Nabi
Azad informed the Rajya Sabha [Council of States] that clinical and
epidemiological data suggested that it was an outbreak of acute
encephalitis syndrome, resulting in 150 cases and 55 deaths, mostly
among children. In a written reply, the minister said these cases were
reported from early June to mid-July [2011] from Muzaffarpur and its
bordering areas.

